ce:section.ce:para:
The loading capacity of antibiotics into the CQDs was investigated by employing azithromycin (AZI, a macrolide antibiotic) and tobramycin (TOB, an aminoglycoside antibiotic). With an increase in the mass ratio of antibiotics to CQDs from 5:1 to 50:1, the loading capacity of AZI and TOB increased from approximately 0.5 to 11 mg/mg (CQDs) and 0.5 to 6 mg/mg (CQDs), respectively (Fig. 2
                     ). However, the antibiotic loading appeared to decrease after reconstitution of these freeze-dried CQDs-antibiotic composites (Table S1), which may be due to the desorption of loosely bound antibiotic molecules from CQDs during the freeze drying process. The observation suggests that, in addition to the physical sorption, some other mechanism may involve in the formation of the CQDs-antibiotic composites. To further identify the possible mechanism of the interaction between antibiotics and the CQDs, FTIR spectra of the antibiotics, CQDs and CQDs-antibiotic composites in solid state were acquired using attenuated total reflectance (ATR) (Fig. 3
                     ). The characteristic absorption peak at 3400 cm−1 (assigned to the OH stretching region [21]) of AZI disappeared in the FTIR spectrum of the CQDs-AZI composite. Similarly, the characteristic absorption peaks at 3450–3200 and 1588 cm−1 (assigned to NH stretching and bending, respectively [22]) of TOB broadened in the FTIR spectrum of the CQDs-TOB composite. Correspondingly, the absorption peak at 1746 cm−1 (assigned to CO stretching [17]) of the CQDs broadened in the CQDs-antibiotic composites. These observations indicate the formation of intermolecular hydrogen bonding between the CO groups of the CQDs and the OH groups of AZI, and between the CO groups of the CQDs and the NH groups of TOB. Hence, although beyond the scope of the present study, the optimization of the surface passivation of CQDs could further improve the loading capacity of specific drug molecules into CQDs.

To investigate the roles of the CQDs in the formulation, the antibiotic-loaded CQD-PLGA hybrid nanoparticles were prepared with varying the content of the CQDs in the formulation (Table 1
                     ). Both AZI-loaded and TOB-loaded CQD-PLGA hybrid nanoparticles exhibited sizes smaller than 150 nm with low PDI (0.13–0.22). The zeta potentials of the antibiotics-loaded CQD-PLGA hybrid nanoparticles were characterized in the range of −40 to −50 mV, which offers the sufficient repulsive force to attain good colloidal stability. The drug loading (DL) of the resulting CQD-PLGA hybrid nanoparticles was approximately 12 to 14% for both AZI and TOB, which is approximately 3 times higher than that of the AZI-loaded PLGA nanoparticles (about 4% DL) as described in our previous study [19]. This can be explained by that the formation of the CQDs-antibiotic composites restricts the diffusion of the antibiotic molecules during the nanoparticle formation, consequently, leading to the co-precipitation of PLGA with CQDs-antibiotic composites [23]. It is worth to mention that the DL can be further increased up to about 30% by optimizing the formulation parameters (Fig. S3). In vitro release of AZI and TOB from the CQD-PLGA hybrid nanoparticles was characterized by using a dialysis method [19]. More than 80% of non-encapsulated antibiotics (both AZI and TOB) diffused from the dialysis bag within 4 h (Fig. 4
                     a), confirming that the dialysis bag did not constitute an important barrier to drug release. Encapsulation of the antibiotics into the CQD-PLGA hybrid nanoparticles provided sustained release of the antibiotics up to at least 72 h (Fig. 4b, c). In addition, increasing the CQD content in the nanoparticle formulations resulted in decreased initial burst release of both AZI and TOB within the first 4 h (Fig. 4b, c). These observations indicate that co-encapsulating CQDs into PLGA matrix can effectively impede the antibiotic release from PLGA matrix possibly due to the interaction of the CQDs with the antibiotic molecules (both AZI and TOB). In addition, increasing the content of the CQDs in PLGA nanoparticles enhances the diffusional barrier. However, considering the potential influence of the CQDs content in the nanoscale structure and/or the porosity of the nanoparticles, it is likely that the optimal CQDs content should be investigated in the future study. The NIR-triggered release of antibiotics was investigated by irradiating nanoparticle formulation C and F with the 808 nm laser for 3 min at a power density of 3 W/cm2. The released drugs (both AZI and TOB) in the absence of NIR irradiation amounted to about 15%, 20%, and 25% at 2, 4 and 7 h, respectively. In comparison, upon irradiation at 2, 4 and 7 h, the CQD-PLGA hybrid nanoparticles released approximately 25% AZI and 25% TOB during 4 h, approximately 45% AZI and 55% TOB during 7 h, approximately 60% AZI and 80% TOB during 24 h, respectively (Fig. 4d). The NIR-triggered release likely results from the fact that the laser irradiation leads to a temperature increasing close to or above the glass transition temperature (Tg) of PLGA (approximately 40–42 °C [24]), thus, inducing a phase transition and influencing the nanoscale network of PLGA in the nanoparticles, subsequently accelerating drug release [25]. The NIR-triggered release enables the antibiotic concentration reaching to the therapeutic level in a shorter period. Meanwhile, the unreleased portion of the drugs can further maintain the therapeutic concentration for a longer period. Thus, the unique stimuli-responsive release pattern may offer great advantage in enhancing the antimicrobial efficacy. In this regard, the optimal stimuli-responsive release pattern should be investigated in the future study.
